{
 "response": "# Perspective Audit \u2014 Tab Panel Without Arrow Key Navigation\n\n## Step 1 \u2014 Escalated perspectives confirmed\n\nFrom the a11y-critic hand-off:\n\n- **Keyboard & Motor Access** \u2014 HIGH \u2192 deep review\n- **Screen Reader & Semantic Structure** \u2014 HIGH \u2192 deep review\n\nPerspectives at LOW (not reviewed): Magnification & Reflow, Environmental Contrast, Vestibular & Motion, Auditory Access, Cognitive & Neurodivergent.\n\n## Step 2 \u2014 Reference sections loaded\n\nRead the JTBD checklists for perspectives 5 (Keyboard & Motor) and 6 (Screen Reader & Semantic) only, plus the ARRM perspective-to-role mapping in full for routing.\n\n## Step 3 \u2014 Artifact under review\n\nReact `TabPanel` component (single file) with companion CSS. Four tabs (Overview, Specifications, Reviews, Support) rendered as native `<button>` elements inside a plain `<div className=\"tab-bar\">`; four panels rendered as `<div className=\"tab-panel\">` toggled with inline `display: none`/`block`. State held in `useState('overview')`; `handleTabClick` sets the active tab on click. No ARIA roles, no `aria-selected`, no `aria-controls`/`aria-labelledby`, no arrow-key handling. Focus-visible outline and a color+underline active indicator are present in CSS.\n\n---\n\n## Step 4 \u2014 Perspective 5: Keyboard & Motor Access\n\n**WCAG (AA):** 1.3.4, 2.1.1, 2.1.2, 2.4.1, 2.4.3, 2.4.7, 2.4.13, 2.5.1, 2.5.2, 2.5.3, 2.5.7, 2.5.8\n\n| # | Checklist item (WCAG) | Result | Evidence |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | All interactive elements reachable/operable by keyboard alone (2.1.1) | **PASS** | Tabs are native `<button>` elements. All four sit in the natural tab order (no roving tabindex), each activates via Enter/Space. Every tab and every panel's content is keyboard-reachable today. |\n| 2 | No keyboard trap (2.1.2) | **PASS** | Tab / Shift+Tab move through the four buttons and out; nothing captures focus. |\n| 3 | Skip link targets main content (2.4.1) | **N/A** | Page-level concern; out of component scope. |\n| 4 | Focus order logical (2.4.3) | **PASS** | DOM order = tab bar buttons, then the visible panel. Matches visual reading order; inactive panels are `display:none` and removed from focus order. |\n| 5 | Focus indicator \u22652px, \u22653:1 contrast, not obscured (2.4.7, 2.4.11) | **PASS** | `.tab-btn:focus-visible { outline: 3px solid #005fcc; outline-offset: 2px; }` (CSS). A 3px offset outline in high-contrast blue on the white surface is clearly visible and not clipped by any sticky element. |\n| 6 | Multi-point gestures have single-pointer alternative (2.5.1) | **N/A** | No gestures. |\n| 7 | Activation on up-event, abortable (2.5.2) | **PASS** | `onClick` fires on pointer-up; no `onMouseDown` activation. |\n| 8 | Visible label = accessible name (2.5.3) | **PASS** | Button text (\"Overview\", etc.) is the accessible name; no overriding `aria-label`. |\n| 9 | Drag has click alternative (2.5.7) | **N/A** | No drag. |\n| 10 | Targets \u2265 24\u00d724 CSS px (2.5.8) | **PASS** | `.tab-btn { padding: 10px 20px }` yields \u224838px height and >24px width. |\n| 11 | Portrait + landscape (1.3.4) | **PASS** | No orientation lock; `display:flex` tab bar reflows. |\n\n**Red flags checked:** interactive element unreachable by keyboard \u2014 does **not** fire (all reachable). Keyboard trap \u2014 does not fire. Drag-only \u2014 does not fire. `outline:none` with no replacement \u2014 does not fire (focus-visible outline present). **No auto-CRITICAL red flag fires for this perspective.**\n\n**Honest calibration note:** In its *current* markup the keyboard-operability checklist essentially passes \u2014 all four tabs are Tab-reachable and Enter/Space-activatable. The missing ArrowLeft/Right navigation is **not a standalone WCAG 2.1.1 failure**: WCAG does not mandate arrow keys, and the buttons are independently tabbable. Rating the arrow-key gap CRITICAL on rule weight alone would be a dead finding. The real defect is an interaction-model mismatch that is inseparable from the semantic fix \u2014 see below.\n\n### Finding K1\n\n**Finding:** The component presents as a tabbed interface (visual tab bar, active underline) but implements the APG **Tabs** *keyboard* contract nowhere \u2014 no ArrowLeft/ArrowRight to move between tabs, no Home/End, no roving `tabindex`. A keyboard user who recognizes the tab affordance gets no arrow-key behavior and must Tab through all four controls. More importantly, the mandated screen-reader remediation (adding `role=\"tab\"` \u2014 see SR1) **requires** this keyboard pattern to be added in lockstep: if `role=\"tab\"` is introduced with the APG-required roving `tabindex` (active tab `tabindex=\"0\"`, others `tabindex=\"-1\"`) but **without** arrow-key handlers, three of the four tabs become keyboard-**unreachable** \u2014 a CRITICAL regression manufactured out of a partial fix.\n**WCAG:** 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value (APG Tabs keyboard pattern); interaction expectation under 2.1.1 Keyboard\n**Perspective:** Keyboard & Motor Access\n**Severity:** MAJOR\n**Route to:** Front-End Dev (secondary: UX Design)\n**Evidence:** Fixture code \u2014 `handleTabClick` only calls `setActiveTab`; the component's own comment marks it: \"No Arrow key handling \u2014 only Tab/click switches panels.\" Tab bar `<div className=\"tab-bar\">` and `<button>` elements carry no `tabindex` management. Current standalone impact is limited (all four tabs Tab-reachable); severity is MAJOR because the widget must become a real tabs pattern and the entire keyboard contract is absent, and because a role-only fix regresses keyboard access to CRITICAL.\n**Fix:** Implement the APG Tabs keyboard behavior together with the ARIA roles from SR1: roving `tabindex` on the tab group; ArrowLeft/ArrowRight to move roving focus (wrapping at ends); Home/End to jump to first/last tab; Enter/Space (or automatic-on-focus, if using automatic activation) to select. Give the active `tabpanel` `tabindex=\"0\"` so it is focusable when it contains no focusable children. **Ship K1 and SR1 as one atomic change \u2014 never roles without keys.**\n\n---\n\n## Step 4 \u2014 Perspective 6: Screen Reader & Semantic Structure\n\n**WCAG (AA):** 1.1.1, 1.3.1, 1.3.2, 2.4.2, 2.4.4, 2.4.6, 3.1.1, 3.1.2, 3.3.1, 3.3.2, 4.1.2, 4.1.3\n\n| # | Checklist item (WCAG) | Result | Evidence |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | Landmark regions present/correct (1.3.1) | **PASS (note)** | `<section>` wraps the widget; with no accessible name it is a generic container, not an exposed landmark. Acceptable at component scope (an `<h2>` provides structure). Labeling the section is an enhancement, not a violation. |\n| 2 | Heading hierarchy logical (2.4.6) | **PASS** | Single `<h2>Product Details</h2>`; assumes an `<h1>` exists on the host page. |\n| 3 | Informative images have alt (1.1.1) | **N/A** | No images. |\n| 4 | DOM order = visual order (1.3.2) | **PASS** | Tab bar then active panel. |\n| 5 | Unique descriptive `<title>` (2.4.2) | **N/A** | Component scope. |\n| 6 | Link text descriptive (2.4.4) | **N/A** | No links. |\n| 7 | `lang` on `<html>` (3.1.1) | **N/A** | Component scope. |\n| 8 | Foreign phrases wrapped (3.1.2) | **N/A** | None. |\n| 9 | Inputs have associated labels (3.3.2) | **N/A** | No form inputs (buttons carry visible text names). |\n| 10 | Errors identify field via `aria-describedby` (3.3.1) | **N/A** | No forms/errors. |\n| 11 | Custom widgets use correct ARIA roles per APG (4.1.2) | **FINDING (SR1)** | `<div className=\"tab-bar\">` has no `role=\"tablist\"`; `<button>`s have no `role=\"tab\"`, `aria-selected`, or `aria-controls`; panels have no `role=\"tabpanel\"` or `aria-labelledby`. |\n| 12 | Selected/active state programmatically exposed (4.1.2) | **FINDING (SR2)** | Active state is expressed only visually via `.tab-btn.active` (color + underline). No `aria-selected`; AT cannot determine the current tab. |\n| 13 | Status messages use `aria-live` at right urgency (4.1.3) | **N/A (deliberate)** | A correct tabs pattern conveys the panel change through `aria-selected` + focus, **not** a live region. Adding `aria-live` here would apply the wrong APG pattern. No 4.1.3 finding is raised \u2014 flagging one would be a false alarm. |\n| 14 | SPA route changes announced/focus-managed | **N/A** | No routing. |\n\n**Red flags checked:** No `<main>` landmark \u2014 N/A (component scope). Form input without label \u2014 N/A. Missing `lang` \u2014 N/A. \"Custom widget with no ARIA role\" \u2014 **does not cleanly fire**: the interactive controls are native `<button>` elements, so each exposes an implicit `button` role and is announced and operable. The failure is not *rolelessness* (which would auto-CRITICAL); it is that the controls carry the **wrong** role for the pattern (`button` instead of `tab`) and omit the selected-state and tab\u2194panel relationships. Calibrating to MAJOR (not auto-CRITICAL) because content remains reachable and each control is labeled and operable \u2014 impact-based severity per the perspective's calibration table, not rule weight.\n\n### Finding SR1\n\n**Finding:** The tabbed interface exposes no tab semantics. A screen-reader user hears four ordinary buttons (\"Overview\", \"Specifications\", \"Reviews\", \"Support\") followed by a block of text, with no signal that this is a tab set, no count (\"tab, 1 of 4\"), no relationship between a tab and the panel it controls, and no accessible name tying the visible panel back to its tab. The interface's fundamental nature and structure are hidden from assistive technology.\n**WCAG:** 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value (also 1.3.1 Info and Relationships)\n**Perspective:** Screen Reader & Semantic Structure\n**Severity:** MAJOR\n**Route to:** Front-End Dev (secondary: none \u2014 structural ARIA, not editorial content)\n**Evidence:** Fixture code \u2014 `<div className=\"tab-bar\">` (own comment: \"No role=\\\"tablist\\\" \u2014 this is a plain div\"); each `<button>` (own comment: \"No role=\\\"tab\\\", no aria-selected, no aria-controls\"); each panel `<div className=\"tab-panel\">` (own comment: \"No role=\\\"tabpanel\\\", no aria-labelledby\"). Not CRITICAL because the labeled native buttons remain operable and all panel text is browsable; MAJOR because the tabbed model and tab/panel relationships are entirely absent from the accessibility tree.\n**Fix:** Add `role=\"tablist\"` to the tab container; `role=\"tab\"` + `id` + `aria-controls=\"<panelId>\"` to each button; `role=\"tabpanel\"` + `id` + `aria-labelledby=\"<tabId>\"` to each panel. Give the active panel `tabindex=\"0\"` (no focusable children). Optionally label the tablist with `aria-label` (e.g., \"Product details\"). Implement together with the keyboard pattern in K1.\n\n### Finding SR2\n\n**Finding:** The active tab is conveyed to sighted users by color and an underline, but there is no `aria-selected` on any tab. A screen-reader user cannot determine which tab is currently selected, and activating a tab produces no perceivable change \u2014 no state update, no announcement \u2014 so the interaction appears to do nothing.\n**WCAG:** 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value (missing `value`/state)\n**Perspective:** Screen Reader & Semantic Structure\n**Severity:** MAJOR\n**Route to:** Front-End Dev (secondary: none)\n**Evidence:** Fixture code \u2014 active state exists only in CSS: `.tab-btn.active { color:#1565c0; border-bottom-color:#1565c0; }`, driven by the JS `className` toggle (`activeTab === tab.id ? 'active' : ''`). No `aria-selected` attribute anywhere. Note: visually the state uses **both** color and an underline, so 1.4.1 Use of Color is satisfied for sighted users \u2014 the defect is purely the absent programmatic equivalent for AT.\n**Fix:** Set `aria-selected=\"true\"` on the active tab and `aria-selected=\"false\"` on the others, updated from the same `activeTab` state that drives the `active` class. With `role=\"tab\"` (SR1) in place, screen readers will then announce \"selected\" and reflect changes on activation. No `aria-live` region is needed or appropriate.\n\n---\n\n## Step 6 \u2014 Perspective Audit Summary\n\n**Component/artifact reviewed:** `TabPanel` React component (tabs + panels) with companion CSS\n**Perspectives escalated for deep review:** Keyboard & Motor Access (HIGH); Screen Reader & Semantic Structure (HIGH)\n**Perspectives at LOW (not reviewed):** Magnification & Reflow; Environmental Contrast; Vestibular & Motion; Auditory Access; Cognitive & Neurodivergent\n\n### Findings by Severity\n\n| Severity | Count |\n|---|---|\n| CRITICAL | 0 |\n| MAJOR | 3 |\n| MINOR | 0 |\n| ENHANCEMENT | 0 |\n\n### Perspectives That Passed\n\nNone passed outright. Keyboard & Motor passed the **operability** checklist (no red flags, all content keyboard-reachable) but carries one MAJOR interaction-model finding coupled to the semantic fix.\n\n### Perspectives With Findings \u2014 Grouped by ARRM Role\n\n**Front-End Dev**\n- Tabs widget does not implement the APG keyboard pattern (arrow keys / Home-End / roving tabindex) \u2014 Keyboard & Motor \u2014 MAJOR \u2014 4.1.2 (K1)\n- No tab/tablist/tabpanel roles or tab\u2194panel relationships \u2014 Screen Reader & Semantic \u2014 MAJOR \u2014 4.1.2 / 1.3.1 (SR1)\n- Selected state exposed to sighted users only; no `aria-selected` \u2014 Screen Reader & Semantic \u2014 MAJOR \u2014 4.1.2 (SR2)\n\n**UX Design**\n- (secondary on K1) Confirm activation model \u2014 manual activation (Enter/Space) vs. automatic activation (select on arrow focus) \u2014 before implementation.\n\n**Visual Design** \u2014 none.\n\n**Content Author** \u2014 none.\n\n### Cross-Perspective Note (critical for remediation sequencing)\n\nThe two escalated perspectives are one coupled defect. The screen-reader fix (`role=\"tab\"` + roving `tabindex`) **mandates** the keyboard fix (arrow keys + Home/End). Shipping ARIA roles without the keyboard handlers converts a MINOR/MAJOR keyboard gap into a **CRITICAL** one: under APG roving `tabindex`, only the active tab is Tab-focusable, so without arrow keys the other three tabs become keyboard-unreachable. **K1, SR1, and SR2 must ship as a single atomic change.** Today's plain-button implementation is, paradoxically, *more* keyboard-reachable than a half-finished fix.\n\n### Open Questions Requiring Human Verification\n\nNone. All three findings are code-level and fully confirmable from source. There is no media, imagery, or editorial copy in scope, so there are no content-author verification items (no caption accuracy, transcript, alt-text, or reading-level checks).\n\n### Recommended Next Step\n\n**REVISE** \u2014 MAJOR findings present, no CRITICAL. Address K1 + SR1 + SR2 as one atomic implementation of the WAI-ARIA APG Tabs pattern before shipping. Although no finding is rated CRITICAL, the screen-reader barrier (unperceivable selected state, no feedback on activation) is serious; treat this as blocking for AT users. Re-test with `a11y-test` (real keyboard events for arrow/Home/End navigation; screen-reader verification of `role=\"tab\"` announcement and `aria-selected` state changes) after the fix.\n\n---\n\n## Emitted A11y Evidence Findings (new MAJOR findings from deep review)\n\n### A11y Evidence Finding\nfinding_id: tabpanel-missing-tab-roles\nfingerprint: 4a1f7c2e9b3d5680\nsource: perspective-audit Screen Reader & Semantic Structure checklist\nwcag_or_apg: WCAG 2.2 SC 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value; WAI-ARIA APG Tabs pattern\nsection_508_fpc_context: Revised Section 508 incorporates WCAG 2.0 A/AA; 4.1.2 is in scope\nseverity: MAJOR\nperspective_alarms: keyboard_motor=HIGH; screen_reader_semantic=HIGH\nevidence: Fixture \u2014 `<div className=\"tab-bar\">` (no role=tablist), `<button>` tabs (no role=tab/aria-selected/aria-controls), panel `<div className=\"tab-panel\">` (no role=tabpanel/aria-labelledby)\nreproduction_steps: source review only; confirm with screen reader \u2014 navigate tab bar, no \"tab list / tab / selected\" semantics announced\nexpected_behavior: SR announces a tablist of 4 tabs, the selected tab, and the associated panel\nactual_behavior: SR announces four generic buttons and an unrelated text block\ntrend: new\n\n### A11y Evidence Finding\nfinding_id: tabpanel-selected-state-visual-only\nfingerprint: b7e0d9143f6a2c58\nsource: perspective-audit Screen Reader & Semantic Structure checklist\nwcag_or_apg: WCAG 2.2 SC 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value (state/value)\nsection_508_fpc_context: Revised Section 508 incorporates WCAG 2.0 A/AA; 4.1.2 is in scope\nseverity: MAJOR\nperspective_alarms: screen_reader_semantic=HIGH\nevidence: Active state only in CSS `.tab-btn.active` (color + underline) via className toggle; no aria-selected attribute\nreproduction_steps: source review only; activate a tab with a screen reader running\nexpected_behavior: newly selected tab announces \"selected\"; state queryable programmatically\nactual_behavior: no state change is exposed; activation is silent to AT\ntrend: new\n\n### A11y Evidence Finding\nfinding_id: tabpanel-missing-apg-keyboard-pattern\nfingerprint: c3a58f21e740b6d9\nsource: perspective-audit Keyboard & Motor Access checklist\nwcag_or_apg: WCAG 2.2 SC 4.1.2 (APG Tabs keyboard contract); SC 2.1.1 interaction expectation\nsection_508_fpc_context: Revised Section 508 incorporates WCAG 2.0 A/AA; 2.1.1/4.1.2 in scope\nseverity: MAJOR\nperspective_alarms: keyboard_motor=HIGH\nevidence: `handleTabClick` sets state only (\"No Arrow key handling\" per source comment); no roving tabindex, no Arrow/Home/End handlers\nreproduction_steps: keyboard test \u2014 focus a tab, press ArrowRight/ArrowLeft/Home/End; no roving focus movement occurs\nexpected_behavior: Arrow keys move between tabs, Home/End jump to first/last, roving tabindex keeps one tab-stop\nactual_behavior: arrow keys do nothing; all four tabs are individual tab-stops (fix-coupling risk: adding roving tabindex without arrows makes 3 of 4 tabs keyboard-unreachable)\ntrend: new\n",
